Wk26 Overview of the nephron, waste production and filtration/secretion in the kidney 

Thursday, October 5, 2017 

1:27 PM 

Describe the dietary sources and production of metabolic waste- what are the waste products and where do they come from? 

 

 

The kidneys remove mainly water (95%), solutes (sulfates, phosphates, Na+, K+, Ca2+, Mg2+, HCO3-) and other wastes such as nitrogen compounds (ammonium, urea, creatinine, drug by-products). The fluid flowing into the nephrons is known as the filtrate, and useful products can be reabsorbed from this filtrate.  

 

Nitrogenous source 

A main source of nitrogenous waste is the normal metabolism of protein. Deamination in the liver removes NH2-, and this will combine with H+ to form NH3. NH3 enters the urea cycle to form urea, as this is much less toxic. Plasma urea concentration is usually linked to protein intake (dietary protein is the main factor). 

 

Another source of nitrogenous waste may be the metabolism of nucleic acids. Nucleic acids are commonly recycled, but if metabolised pyrimidines (C, U, T) are metabolised to NH4+ and purines (A, G) are metabolised to uric acid.  

 

Note: the urea cycle takes place in the mitochondria and cytosol of a hepatocyte. 

 

Creatinine is the breakdown product of creatine and creatine phosphate. There may be a higher concentration of plasma creatine in individuals with larger muscle bulk.  

 

Describe the general metabolic and cellular consequences of waste buildup  

-Azotemia is an increased level of circulating nitrogenous products, indicated by an increased blood urea nitrogen level. Nitrogenous wastes (primarily urea and creatinine) are toxic to the CNS and cause confusion, seizures, and coma. They can also impact the digestive system by causing the loss of appetite, nausea, and mucosal bleeding. Pruritus and uremic frost can appear on skin. Sweet-smelling breath or sweat may also occur.  

-Hyperuricemia indicates an increased urate concentration, and can cause gout (acute joint arthritis) due to monosodiumurate precipitation in joints; and can also cause nephrolithiasis (kidney stones, crystal forms in renal pelvis). 

 

Differentiate the two mechanisms of renal excretion of waste (filtration vs excretion) 

Glomerular filtration is a passive process, driven by hydrostatic pressure. Water and solutes pass through the glomerulus into the tubule as the filtrate, whilst blood cells and proteins do not. Note that filtration has a net filtration pressure of around 10mmHg (55mmHg blood hydrostatic pressure - 15mmHg capsular hydrostatic pressure - 30mmHg oncotic pressure).  

 

Renal tubular secretion is an ATP-dependent process by which poisons which do not enter the filtrate and instead pass the glomerulus into the venous capillaries are pumped into the tubule nonetheless. Hence,  

 

Excretion = Filtration - Reabsorption + Secretion 

 

 

Describe the glomerular filtration membrane in detail 

There are 3 components to the glomerular membrane. The fenestrated pore of the glomerular endothelial cell prevents the filtration of blood cells but allows other plasma components through. Then, the basal lamina of the glomerulus directly outside of this prevents the filtration of larger proteins. Then, the slit membrane between pedicles prevents the filtration of medium-sized proteins. Past these slits, the fluid has entered the Bowman's capsule.  

 

 

Describe which blood constituents are filtered and which retained, and the basis of this selectivity 

Endothelial cells are porous (70nm wide pores), and have negatively charged podocalyxin. The glomerular basement membrane contains 3 layers and contain negatively charged glycoproteins. Epithelial cells (podocytes) contain filtration slits (25-65nm wide). Only substances smaller than the pores are able to pass through, and anions are less likely to be filtered due to repulsion.  

 

Describe the useful molecules that are filtered by the glomerulus and the site/method of their reabsorption 

The proximal convoluted tubule reabsorbs Na+, HCO3-, glucose, amino acids, and many other ions/nutrients. H2O is reabsorbed in the descending loop of Henle. Na+, K+, Cl- are reabsorbed in the ascending loop. The distal convoluted tubule reabsorbs Na+ (and hence followed by Cl-) through aldosterone regulation, and Ca2+ by parathyroid hormone. The collecting ducts adjust for pH, reabsorb more water, and reabsorb urea to maintain osmolarity.  

 

Describe the waste molecules that are secreted in the tubules and the site/method of secretion 

NH4+ is secreted from the bloodstream into the proximal tubule. Note that some NH3 would have diffused into the filtrate too. This increased basicity allows increased H+ secretion or HCO3- reabsorption. Urea is secreted into the tubule at the ascending limb of the loop of Henle. K+ is secreted into both the distal tubule and collecting duct via regulatory means.
